" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "As you know (should know if you have encountered c
ertain ideas " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "in your Number Theory st
udies, or will eventually know at some " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
64 "further point in your studies), the behaviour of the congruence " 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 68 "x^2 + 1 = 0 (mod m) depends very subtly
 on the arithmetic strucrure " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 26 "of the n
atural number \"m\"." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 12 "For example:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "1. If m = p, is a prime that is congruent to 3 \+
modulo 4," }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 61 "    then the congruence x^2 \+
+ 1 = 0 (mod m) has NO solutions." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "    \+
Thus x^2 + 1 = 0 (mod m) has NO solutions for these values:" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 73 "    m = 3, 7, 11, 19, 23, 31, 43, ... (there ar
e infinitely many of them," }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "    as you \+
should - or will - know.)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 56 "2. More generally than 1, if m is DIVISIBLE by a p
rime p" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 54 "    that is congruent to 3 mod \+
4, then the congruence " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 63 "    x^2 + 1 = \+
0 (mod m) has NO solutions. SO, no solutions for:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 66 "    m = 3, 6, 7, 11, 12, 14, 15, 18, 19, 21, 22, 23, 24, \+
27, ... ." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
52 "3. If m = p, is a prime congruent to 1 modulo 4,    " }}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 59 "    then the congruence x^2 + 1 = 0 (mod m) has EX
ACTLY two" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 66 "    \"mutually incongruent\"
 solutions. So, there are two DIFFERENT " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
39 "    solutions for the following values:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 72 "    m = 5, 13, 17, 29, 37, 41, 53, 61, 73, ... (infinitely many
 values.)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
62 "4. Of course if m = 2, then the congruence x^2 + 1 = 0 (mod m)" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 66 "    has just one solution: x = 1 (mod 2),
